        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-11-27T20:01:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-11-27T20:01:00-05:00" n="296"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                <head>296. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Cyprus</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d296fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, POL 15–5 Cyp. Confidential; Priority. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BK2">Bracken</persName> and Schott and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_TP1">Talbot</persName>. Repeated to Athens, Ankara, and
                        London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-11-27T20:01:00-05:00">November 27, 1963, 8:01 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>225. Ref: Nicosia’s 295.<note n="1" xml:id="d296fn1">
                        <ref target="#d295">Document 295</ref>.</note> Deputy <gloss target="#t_PM1"
                        >PM</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d296fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName> was a member of the Greek
                        delegation attending the funeral of President <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                            >John F. Kennedy</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_KJF1"
                            >Kennedy</persName> was assassinated in Dallas on November 22.</note>
                    made following points on Cyprus problem during recent contacts with Department
                    officers: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>He said it was essential make some amendments to Cyprus constitution
                            and indicated <gloss target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss> has British support.
                            He had spoken to <persName corresp="#p_II1">Inonu</persName> and
                                <persName corresp="#p_EF1">Erkin</persName> here in Washington in
                            general terms about Greek-Turkish problems and will see latter again at
                                <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> meeting and when guarantor
                            powers meet in Paris. <persName corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName>
                            asked that we contribute finding solution. <persName corresp="#p_MIIIA1"
                                >Makarios</persName> envisages matter as question of negotiation
                            amend certain articles constitution while simultaneously making some
                            concessions to Turks. In response we reiterated our interest maintaining
                            good Greek-Turk relations and stable Cyprus and hoped <gloss
                                target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss> would talk with <gloss target="#t_GOT1"
                                >GOT</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>. Emphasized hope
                            for solution through negotiation between parties directly
                            involved.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>British Embassy Washington informed of general pitch of <persName
                                corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName> statements.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">For Nicosia:</hi> We commend points made your response
                                <persName corresp="#p_MIIIA1">Makarios</persName> plans disclosed
                            reftel. Seek early opportunity inform <persName corresp="#p_MIIIA1"
                                >Makarios</persName> we are greatly disturbed at his constant
                            references to “amendments” of constitution. Our reading of situation is
                            that presentation of such a memorandum to guarantor powers as stated
                            would stop <gloss target="#t_GOT1">GOT</gloss> and Turk-Cypriot
                            cooperation before it got started and that ultimately he needs this
                            cooperation to solve problem.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">For Athens:</hi>
                            <persName corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName>’ several references in
                            Washington conversations to amendments also cause concern. We believe he
                            has misread British support for his position.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
